column1: As Medical Director of Quality, I am interested in applying principles of high reliability to the intensive care unit environments of SmartterHealth hospital to prevent harm, discover problems, and work collaboratively toward solutions. In addition I am a proponent of maximizing performance transparency. My current projects include using resilience engineering to minimize unnecessary variation in the delivery of care, specifically for pediatric septic shock and pediatric stroke. I also am working on a project to determine the clinical utility of noninvasive measurements of cardiac performance indices in pediatric patients.

column1:
I received my medical degree from The Boucher Institute of Naturopathic Medicine in 2011. After a year working at a private medical clinic in Vancouver BC, I moved to Los Angeles and have been in practice at Synergy Natural Medicine Clinic in Monrovia, CA since 2012.

Prior to receiving my medical degree, I obtained a degree in psychology and worked as a social worker. In 2006, I volunteered as a relief worker through Global Resource Alliance, helping traditional healers provide primary care to the local villages in Musoma, Tanzania. This transformative experience resulted in my application to naturopathic medical school as soon as I returned home from Africa.

column1: Primary care of the pediatric age-group is an essential part of civilization. This includes simple adjustments in lifestyle that help children stay healthy or get on the path to a healthy life.

I have almost 7 years worth of experience in my field and have a reputation for always striving to not only meet my goals but surpass them. When I am part of a team I like to bring a positive energy and upbeat attitude and bring that energy and motivation out of others as well.
